{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522128"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13807"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13807"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.76,0.1,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50581"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"1608"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6111"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11560"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12757"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50581"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with right shoulder girdle discomfort and occasional weakness when trying to lift his right shoulder. He had a right chest drain insertion for a traumatic pneumothorax a few months prior. He is otherwise fit and well. He has no previous surgery to the chest. He denies any other recent trauma. On examination, when he tries to push himself against the wall with his right hand, the sign shown in the photograph is revealed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely injured to explain this clinical finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thoracodorsal nerve","Long thoracic nerve","Suprascapular nerve","Axillary nerve","Intercostal nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical finding described in this scenario is consistent with scapular winging, which is characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Elong thoracic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury. This nerve innervates the serratus anterior muscle, which is responsible for stabilizing the scapula against the chest wall and rotating it during arm elevation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen the \u003Cstrong\u003Elong thoracic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is injured, the serratus anterior muscle becomes weak or paralyzed, leading to the prominent medial border of the scapula (winging) when the patient pushes against a wall. The history of chest drain insertion is significant, as this procedure can potentially damage the long thoracic nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethoracodorsal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the latissimus dorsi muscle. Injury to this nerve would not cause scapular winging but might affect arm adduction and internal rotation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuprascapular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles. Its injury would affect shoulder abduction and external rotation but would not cause scapular winging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles. Damage to this nerve would primarily affect shoulder abduction and external rotation, not scapular stability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntercostal nerves\u003C/strong\u003E supply the intercostal muscles and skin of the chest wall. Their injury would not directly affect scapular movement or stability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the long thoracic nerve injury best explains the clinical finding of scapular winging in this patient, likely as a complication of the previous chest drain insertion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Long thoracic nerve injury can result in scapular winging, characterized by prominence of the medial border of the scapula when pushing against a wall.","Chest drain insertion is a potential cause of long thoracic nerve injury.","Clinical examination of scapular movement is crucial in diagnosing long thoracic nerve injury."],"references":["https://www.orthobullets.com/shoulder-and-elbow/3062/scapular-winging"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13807"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20750"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20750"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jilLYylSxwaGSJmN4f8zaLtX3DCBY5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jilLYylSxwaGSJmN4f8zaLtX3DCBY5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35800"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-13T20:20:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-13T20:21:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6424"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50581"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","